          "annotations": [
            {
              "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p37d2qq43/canvas/p2/annopage",
              "type": "AnnotationPage",
              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p37d2qq43/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>But there is one consolation that the matter rests in good\n                                        hands<lb/> for as far as I have the honor of knowing you by\n                                        reputation,<lb/> I know that you are <hi rend=\"underline\"\n                                                  >not</hi> the man to give up a project so<lb/>\n                                        easily, if there is the remotest spark of hope, of\n                                        succeeding<lb/> even at an indefinite period, and as far as\n                                        I am con<lb/>cerned, I promise you my aid, as much as my\n                                        feeble efforts<lb/> will permit, so that if the congregation\n                                        can retain me here I hope yet to<lb/> see\n                                                  <placeName>Charleston</placeName>\n                                        <sic>formost</sic> in the successful effort. It strikes\n                                        me<lb/> however, that you could further the matter by the\n                                        following method.<lb/> Engage if possible a competent\n                                        person, friendly to the cause,<lb/> who is to issue an\n                                        anonymous Article, showing all imaginable<lb/> dangers which\n                                                  ultras<add>?</add> think may possibly accrue to\n                                        the cause of our holy Religion<lb/> by the proposed\n                                        convention, let it be worded as if coming from<lb/> a\n                                        hostile pen, and then set about depending anonymously the\n                                        project, ably,<lb/> at the same time laying bare every\n                                        imaginable disadvantage we<lb/> are laboring under at\n                                        present and the deplorable state of religious<lb/> anarchy\n                                        amongst <placeName>Israel</placeName> all over\n                                                  <placeName>America</placeName>. Such a controversy\n                                        would<lb/> draw the attention of the public more\n                                        successfully, those who<lb/> are lukewarm may become\n                                        interested in the matter, while the<lb/> ultra Orthodox will\n                                        gradually yield. I merely suggest this<lb/> because there\n                                        are many here and probably everywhere else, who will\n                                        not<lb/> listen to reason, and merely say, <hi\n                                                  rend=\"underline\">It cannot be done</hi>. One<lb/>\n                                        objects because his neighbor says it is injurious, the\n                                        other, because<lb/> it will cost something, a third, wishes\n                                        to show the public<lb/> that he possess wisdom, and\n                                        foresight. In short there are but<lb/> precious few who\n                                        oppose the measure from true religions</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p37d2qq43/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
            }
